  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, the Department of Commerce recorded $3.2B in contract obligations across 5,967 awards, with an average award size of $530K. Obligations fell 23.9% year over year. These totals are fiscal year to date and therefore partial for the current year. The agency’s spending pattern shows continued reliance on information technology and professional services categories alongside sector-specific buys such as ship repair and aircraft manufacturing. Fiscal-year comparisons show that FY26 to date obligations are lower than several recent full-year totals, including FY24 $5.2B and FY23 $5B, and are closest to FY25 $4.2B. The top categories by dollar value in FY2026 to date concentrate in computer-related services, with Other Computer Related Services at $568M and Computer Systems Design Services at $480M. The vendor list is led by firms providing IT, engineering, and technical services, reflecting the category mix. All figures are contract obligations and current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How has Commerce's contract spending changed year to year?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 23.9% year over year. Fiscal comparisons show FY21 $4.5B, FY22 $4.1B, FY23 $5B, FY24 $5.2B, FY25 $4.2B, and FY26 $3.2B. The FY2026 to date total is lower than the FY24 and FY23 full-year totals. These figures are contract obligations and FY2026 is a partial fiscal-year total."
      },
      {
        "heading": "What categories and vendors dominate FY2026 to date spending?",
        "body": "Top NAICS categories in FY2026 to date are Other Computer Related Services $568M, Computer Systems Design Services $480M, and Custom Computer Programming Services $331M. Other notable categories include All Other Publishers $215M and Ship Building and Repairing $144M. The top vendors in FY2026 to date are REED TECHNOLOGY AND INFORMATION SERVICES LLC $213M, ACCENTURE FEDERAL SERVICES LLC $110M, and LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION $108M. These figures reflect contract obligations for the fiscal-year-to-date period."
      }
    ]
  },
